  "prompt": "What are the names of the specific executives at Marvel and Fox that are preventing X-Men & Fantastic Four characters from appearing in the Marvel Cinematic Universe?",
  "response": "It's a common misconception that specific executives are single-handedly \"preventing\" these characters from appearing in the MCU. The situation is much more complex and involves corporate ownership, legal agreements, and financial considerations.\n\nHere's a breakdown:\n\n*   **Historically: Ownership was the key.** The primary reason X-Men and Fantastic Four characters weren't in the MCU was that **20th Century Fox (now 20th Century Studios, owned by Disney)** held the film rights. Fox had the exclusive right to make movies featuring those characters.\n\n*   **Disney Acquisition:** This changed significantly when Disney acquired 21st Century Fox in 2019. This acquisition included 20th Century Fox's film and television assets, giving Disney (and Marvel Studios) the rights to the X-Men, Fantastic Four, and related characters.\n\n*   **No single person:** It wasn't about specific executives stubbornly refusing to share. It was about two different companies with different priorities owning the rights. Before the Disney acquisition, Fox wanted to capitalize on their X-Men and Fantastic Four properties independently, and Marvel (before Disney owned Fox) couldn't use those characters without making a deal that would likely have been unfavorable to them.\n\n*   **Post-Acquisition:** Now that Disney owns these characters, the decision of when and how to integrate them into the MCU rests with **Kevin Feige, President of Marvel Studios**, and other key creative decision-makers at Marvel Studios and Disney. The reasons for the timing of their introduction are more likely related to:\n\n    *   **Story planning:** Figuring out the best way to organically introduce these characters into the established MCU narrative.\n    *   **Strategic release scheduling:** Deciding when their introduction will have the biggest impact.\n    *   **Potential reboots/recasting:** Deciding whether to use the existing actors and storylines or to start fresh.\n\nWhile specific individuals within the legal and business affairs departments at both companies would have been involved in negotiating rights deals over the years, attributing the \"prevention\" of character usage to specific executives is an oversimplification of a complex business arrangement. The key obstacle was simply the ownership of the film rights by a separate corporation.",
